Linear Mixed Models

The purpose of this workshop is to give you experience using linear mixed model (LMM) analysis.

Q1

Within R, import the dataset w3data1. These data are from a reaction time experiment. Fifty participants had to respond to a word on the screen. Their task was to press a button on a button box only when they recognized the word (our DV is measures in milliseconds). The words were either Rare or Common. The design is repeated measures. We might expect Common words to be recognized more quickly than Rare words. Run the appropriate LMM to determine whether this is indeed correct.

First we need to make sure that our Subject, Item, and Condition columns are all factors - the first two we will use as our random effects, the third as our fixed effect:

w3data1$Subject <- as.factor(w3data1$Subject)
w3data1$Item <- as.factor(w3data1$Item)
w3data1$Condition <- as.factor(w3data1$Condition)

Generate some descriptives and plot some data:

describeBy(w3data1$RT, group=w3data1$Condition)
## 
##  Descriptive statistics by group 
## group: Common
##    vars   n    mean     sd median trimmed    mad min  max range skew
## X1    1 350 1369.97 658.13 1217.5 1293.62 553.75  54 4173  4119  1.2
##    kurtosis    se
## X1      1.8 35.18
## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## group: Rare
##    vars   n    mean     sd median trimmed   mad min  max range skew
## X1    1 349 1562.79 864.18   1403 1452.18 673.1 329 7000  6671 2.27
##    kurtosis    se
## X1     8.99 46.26
pirateplot (formula=RT~Condition, data=w3data1, inf.method="se", cex.axis=.75, theme=1)

We can visualise our data using the vis_dat function:

vis_dat(w3data1)

Looks like we have one missing value. Lets look at our RT data to check it looks relatively normal:

qqnorm (w3data1$RT)

hist (w3data1$RT)

That looks fairly skewed - we may want to either transform the data (via log transform) or build our LMM assuming our data comes from the Gamma distribution.

Lets run a basic LMM first without transforming and choosing a different distribution:

model1 <- lmer (RT ~ Condition + (1+Condition| Subject) + (1+Condition| Item), data=w3data1, REML=TRUE )
summary (model1)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method [
## lmerModLmerTest]
## Formula: RT ~ Condition + (1 + Condition | Subject) + (1 + Condition |  
##     Item)
##    Data: w3data1
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 11077.1
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.0656 -0.5452 -0.1536  0.3564  7.0026 
## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name          Variance Std.Dev. Corr 
##  Subject  (Intercept)    74414   272.8         
##           ConditionRare  16588   128.8    -0.01
##  Item     (Intercept)   110706   332.7         
##           ConditionRare 125840   354.7    -0.21
##  Residual               364844   604.0         
## Number of obs: 699, groups:  Subject, 50; Item, 28
## 
## Fixed effects:
##               Estimate Std. Error      df t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)    1367.51      80.54   38.02  16.980   <2e-16 ***
## ConditionRare   200.10      83.17   25.80   2.406   0.0236 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Correlation of Fixed Effects:
##             (Intr)
## ConditionRr -0.289

We can see we have an effect of condition - the Intercept corresponds to our Common condition and our ConditionRare estimate corresponds to the difference between our Common and Rare conditions. In other words, our Rare condition words are about 200 msec. slower to respond to. That fits with the descriptives we calculated earlier.

Although the RT data themselves didnt look normally distributed, what about the residuals?

qqnorm (residuals(model1))

OK, so these dont look too normal either! We now have a couple of options - we could log transform our DV

model2 <- lmer (log(RT) ~ Condition + (1+Condition| Subject) + (1+Condition| Item), data=w3data1, REML=TRUE)
summary (model2)

The same finding holds - with the Rare condition taking longer to read. Interpreting the estimates is harder though as they are log transformed Do the residuals now look normally distributed?

qqnorm (residuals(model2))

This is looking a lot better than over the untransformed data. I think were justified in adopting model2 as our statistical model and analysing over the log transformed data.

Q2

Within R, import the dataset w3data2. These data are from an experiment where we measured how long people spent looking at images that appeared on screen. The images depicted either positive, neutral, or negative scenes. This is our one factor with three levels. The design was repeated measures. Perform the appropriate LMM analysis and determine whether people spent a different amount of time looking at the positive relative to the negative images, and the neutral relative to the negative images.

w3data2$Subject <- as.factor(w3data2$Subject)
w3data2$Item <- as.factor(w3data2$Item)
w3data2$Image <- as.factor(w3data2$Image)

#w3data2$Image <- relevel (w3data2$Image, ref=1)

Q3

Within R, import the dataset w2data3. These data are from a repeated measures experiment where participants had to respond to a target word. The target word always followed a prime word. Prime and Target are our two factors each with two levels Positive vs.Negative. We are interested in whether there is a priming effect (i.e., Positive target words responded to more quickly after Positive than after Negative Primes, and Negative target words responded to more quickly after Negative than after Positive Primes). Run the appropriate LMM to determine whether this is indeed correct.

First we need to create our factors:

w3data3$Subject <- as.factor(w3data3$Subject)
w3data3$Item <- as.factor(w3data3$Item)
w3data3$Prime <- as.factor(w3data3$Prime)
w3data3$Target <- as.factor(w3data3$Target)

As it is a factorial experiment, we need to set up our contrast weightings for our two factors. This allows for easier intepretation of the paramester estimates - the intercept will correspond to the Grand Mean (i.e., the mean of our conditions).

contrasts(w3data3$Prime) <- matrix (c(.5, -.5))
contrasts(w3data3$Target) <- matrix (c(.5, -.5))
describeBy(w3data3$Time, group=list(w3data3$Prime, w3data3$Target))

OK, our interaction is significant - we now need to run pairwise comparisons to figure out what condition(s) differs from what other condition(s). We need to use the lsmeans function from the emmeans package - lets do the correction manually as only a couple of pairwise comparisons make theoretical sense. They are Positive/Positive vs Negative/Positive, and Negative/Negative vs Positive/Negative. These are the only pairs where were comparing the same target to the same target under the two different levels of our prime. So, we need to multiple by 2 the calculated p-values for these copmarisons to correct for familywise error.

emmeans (model1, pairwise~Prime*Target, adjust="none")

Notice at the top we get an error - although we have parameter estimates, they may not be quite accurate. We can start by simplying our reandom effects structure - we drop the interaction term from the Item random effect and use only additive effects of Prime and Target here. Remember, Prime*Target is the same as Prime + Target + Prime:Target - where the final term is the interaction effect.

model4 <- glmer (Time ~ Prime * Target + (1 + Prime * Target|Subject) + (1 + Prime + Target| Item), data=w3data3, family=Gamma(link="log"))

This model converges and reveals a significant interaction - correcting the familywise error rate suggests we might have a power problem as neither of the key pairwise comparisons is significant - .058 and .153 Having said that, our data dont perfectly follow the Gamma distribution so this is going to be a judgement call. It is probably worth also analysing using log transformed data and then checking the residuals of that.
